 that makes it fun to use and turned it into a billion dollar company.'), (0.015759655916600092, 'Slack is like Twitter for business so why is Twitter failing?'), (0.015729820850450386, 'Within companies it is very important to inform yourself about what’s going on, not only for your job but also for your position within the company and your future ambitions.'), (0.015294968062932892, 'I realised that Twitter misses this social pressure effect because Twitter is focussed on individuals whereas Slack is focussed on teams.'), (0.015122488654887314, 'So the other day this new team member joined our company, got access to Slack and soon afterwards asked the following question:      “Ok…question…I want to post a comment to a previous specific comment, regarding @satya.vh ‘s posting on May 9, but am not seeing an option to do so…can i not do that, or is this just one long continuous thread??'), (0.015097861448512568, 'So just Slack 24/7 and you’ll be fine :-D”  And then it hit me.'), (0.01486712173039649, 'So what you simply need to take into account when building, marketing and selling a social tool like Slack is psychology.'), (0.014791603382823043, 'How to replicate the success  So yes, to replicate Slacks’ success you need a well designed product, an experienced team, perfect timing and amazing execution, as Andrew Wilkonso, Matt Hobb and Slack founder Steward Butterfield rightfully concluded.'), (0.014638715932209806, 'I remembered I found it distractive and stressful because it was so easy to miss out on stuff.'), (0.014295840124089024, 'You need to keep checking or the messages just disappear.'), (0.014263558350969301, 'But honestly, there are tons of startups out there that do this well and have not gained as much traction as Slack.'), (0.01410937112630011, 'Slack has become part of your company and your companies’ culture.'), (0.013737677908975586, 'And before you know there’s no way out.'), (0.013726699388195856, 'I don’t know about you, but I know tons of startups that look, feel and sound different than their competition and fail miserably.'), (0.013704858061727445, 'The free searchable (and viewable limit) is 10.000 messages before you start paying.'), (0.013676801705273401, 'No wonder everyone is analysing how to reproduce this success for their own startup or company.'), (0.013603155227711397, 'It’s addictive, resulting in unconscious stress, because you have the feeling you might miss something.'), (0.013571327740764862, 'If you miss stuff on Slack, oh man, you’re a bad colleague.'), (0.013370941163869486, 'You will become successful if people feel emotionally locked in because of social pressure.'), (0.013277731565936446, 'If you miss stuff on Twitter, nobody cares.'), (0.013080444814338558, 'Now you probably think, yes but there was Yammer before, and Campfire and Hipchat and Skype.'), (0.012877257130886133, 'I see colleagues Slack at night, weekends, days off, when their wife is labouring, etc, which basically put Slack on the same level as email, Facebook and Whatsapp.'), (0.012760338950192818, 'And this pressure makes them invest heavily in your product.'), (0.012716084917857072, 'Being a designer, Andrew’s conclusion is (not that suprising) design focussed: Slack just feels, looks and sounds different than the boring enterprise competition.'), (0.012628022116305813, 'Slack is a dream for every startup founder, investor and VC.'), (0.012622500853987976, 'The reason is that they all either implemented threaded comments or didn’t put a message limit.'), (0.012523381174969386, 'The REAL reason  We’ve been using Slack for over a year now at Fileboard (a sales engagement platform) and basically all our internal communication goes via Slack.'), (0.011982302227248652, 'Sounds like Slack just got lucky then, being there at the right time at the right place with the right people.'), (0.011956165149759789, 'There’s no social isolation effect, no addiction effect and no reason to keep checking.'), (0.011745126921902488, 'A